          "body": "The psalm's final verse is its theological hinge. All the praise of verses 4-8 is grounded in a single *ki*: 'for He is coming to judge.' The coming is described with a participial form — *He is about to come*, imminent and certain. The judge is YHWH Himself, and the standard of His judgment is doubly stated: righteousness (*tsedeq*) and equity (*meshar*). Here the psalm answers its own implicit question: why should the sea roar and the mountains sing at the prospect of judgment? Because judgment by a perfectly righteous and equitable Judge is the only resolution of history's accumulated injustice. The oppressed nations who have watched others prosper unjustly, the creation that has been subjected to futility — all have reason to welcome the coming of the One who will judge without partiality. Keller observed that a God with no wrath is a God who cannot be trusted to care about evil. The psalm's joy is not in spite of the coming judgment but precisely because of it. Psalm 98 finds its New Testament echo in Acts 17:31 ('He has fixed a day in which He will judge the world in righteousness through a Man whom He has appointed') and in Revelation 19:11, where the rider on the white horse judges in righteousness — and His name is the Word of God."
