        "excerpt": "His right hand and His holy arm have gained the victory for Him.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a theological declaration that immediately closes every human boast: YHWH's right hand and holy arm have gained the victory *for Him* — a reflexive construction in Hebrew (*lo*, 'for Himself') that excludes any human co-agent. This is not merely a poetic way of saying God helped; it is an assertion that He acted alone. The background is the Exodus, where YHWH consistently insisted that Israel's smallness, weakness, and failure be the backdrop against which His power alone was displayed (Deuteronomy 7:7-8; 8:17-18). The right hand is the hand of power (Exodus 15:6, 12); the arm is the arm of sovereign action (Isaiah 51:9; 52:10). Their combination names both the executive force and the moral purity by which the victory was achieved.\n\nVerses 2-3 unpack the content and scope of that victory in three clauses. YHWH has made known His *yeshuah* (salvation) — the term is active and historical, not mystical. He has revealed His *tsedaqah* (righteousness) in the sight of the *goyim* (nations) — the revelation is public and internationally visible. And He has *remembered* (*zakhar*) His *chesed* and *emunah* to the house of Israel — His covenantal memory has expressed itself in historical action. The sequencing is important: the universal witness (nations) and the particular covenant (Israel) are presented together in the same two verses, neither canceling the other. YHWH does not abandon His covenant particularity to achieve universal scope; rather, His faithfulness to Israel is the very mechanism by which the nations come to see His salvation.\n\nIsaiah 52:10 — 'The LORD has bared His holy arm in the sight of all the nations, and all the ends of the earth will see the salvation of our God' — is a near-verbatim citation of Psalm 98:2-3, placed by Isaiah in the context of the Servant's suffering and exaltation. This canonical link is crucial: the 'wonderful things' the psalm celebrates are not exhausted by the Exodus or any single historical deliverance. They find their fullest expression in the cross and resurrection, where the right hand of YHWH — the Servant, the Son — achieves a victory entirely by His own power, and the righteousness of God is simultaneously revealed and satisfied (Romans 3:25-26). Paul's argument in Romans 1:16-17 that the gospel is the revelation of the righteousness of God to all — Jew and Gentile — is the New Testament form of this psalm's indicative.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pala* (wonderful things) is the technical term for Exodus-class miracles (Exodus 3:20; 15:11; Psalm 77:14). *Yasah* (gained the victory) carries a reflexive nuance — He worked salvation for Himself, by Himself. *Yeshuah* (salvation) shares its root with the name *Yeshua*; John 4:22 ('salvation is from the Jews') carries this psalm's particular-universal logic."
