        "excerpt": "Shout joyfully before the King, the Lord.",
        "body": "The pivot from indicative to imperative at verse 4 is the psalm's most important structural move. The *ki* of verse 1 ('for He has done wonderful things') is the foundation; the imperatives of verses 4-6 are the prescribed response. The command goes first to 'all the earth' — not to Israel only, not to the nations as a separate category, but to the whole human world as a single addressee. The verb *rua* (shout joyfully) is the coronation shout — used at the anointing of Saul (1 Samuel 10:24) and Solomon (1 Kings 1:39-40), at the dedication of the temple (Ezra 3:11-13), and at the eschatological arrival of the divine King (Zephaniah 3:14; Zechariah 9:9). To use it here is to frame YHWH's act of salvation as a royal enthronement that demands public acclamation.\n\nVerses 5-6 itemize the instruments: the *kinnor* (lyre — David's instrument, the instrument of personal praise and prophecy, 1 Samuel 16:23; 1 Chronicles 25:3), the *zimrah* (melodious song, the vocal dimension), the *chatsotserah* (silver trumpets — the Levitical instruments of Numbers 10:2-10, prescribed for feast days, new moons, and war), and the *shophar* (ram's horn — the instrument of Sinai, Leviticus 25:9, and eschatological arrival, Zechariah 9:14). The list is not random; it is a full mobilization of Israel's liturgical arsenal. The combination of *chatsotserah* and *shophar* in verse 6 is specifically the combination of Numbers 10:2-10 and 2 Chronicles 15:14 — the instruments deployed when Israel assembled before YHWH in covenantal ceremony. The psalm is staging a cosmic coronation ceremony.\n\nThe title 'the King' (*melekh*) appears only here in the psalm — but it is the psalm's theological destination. Every instrument, every voice, every shout has been moving toward this single descriptor. YHWH is not merely the savior of Israel's past; He is the reigning sovereign before whom all the earth currently stands. Tim Keller notes that the psalmists consistently refuse to allow praise to be merely interior and private: the instruments, the communal shout, the public acclamation are not optional extras but the form that corresponds to the reality of a public, historical, visible act of salvation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rua* (shout, v.4 and v.6) — the coronation shout, acoustically sharp and piercing. *Kinnor* (lyre, v.5) — David's instrument; its use alongside temple brass bridges personal devotion and communal liturgy. *Shophar* (ram's horn, v.6) — the eschatological instrument; Matthew 24:31 and 1 Thessalonians 4:16 use the same resonance for the sound accompanying the final coming of the King."
