        "body": "The second imperative movement expands the choir beyond the human world. This expansion is not poetic decoration — it is a theological claim about the scope of God's sovereignty and the scope of coming redemption. The sea, the rivers, and the mountains are not praised for their beauty; they are commanded to praise the One before whom they will shortly be judged. Three natural features are named: the *yam* (sea, the biblical symbol of chaos and threat, Psalm 89:9-10; Isaiah 51:15), the *nahar* (rivers, the fresh-water world of agrarian life), and the *har* (mountains, the most permanent, immovable features of the landscape). Each is given a human gesture: the sea *roars*, the rivers *clap their hands*, the mountains *sing together*.\n\nThe anthropomorphisms (*clap hands*, *sing together*) are the psalm's most striking literary feature. They are not intended to attribute human consciousness to rivers; they are intended to say that if rivers could respond appropriately to the coming of the just King, they would do exactly what hands and voices do in human praise. The personification dramatizes the totality of the response — there is no part of creation that stands outside the call to acclamation. Isaiah 55:12 carries the same image ('the mountains and the hills will break forth into shouts of joy before you, and all the trees of the field will clap their hands') in the context of the return from exile — and Paul brings both streams together in Romans 8:19-22, where creation's eager longing is precisely for the revelation that the psalm's verse 9 announces.\n\nThe verb *yachad* (together, v.8) — *let the mountains sing together* — deserves attention. Mountains do not naturally form a choir; their togetherness is the point. Creation's praise is a communal act, not a simultaneous collection of individual sounds. The same word appears in Psalm 133:1 ('how good and how pleasant it is for brothers to dwell together') and in the Exodus narrative of corporate assembly. The mountains singing *yachad* are a model of the unity that the coming of the righteous Judge makes possible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Raam* (roar, v.7) — the sound of thunder; used of YHWH's voice in Psalm 29:3. *Maach kaph* (clap hands, v.8) — the gesture of acclamation and joy (Psalm 47:1; Isaiah 55:12). *Yachad* (together) — the togetherness of assembly, covenant community, and shared purpose."
