        "excerpt": "For He is coming to judge the earth; He will judge the world with righteousness and the peoples with equity.",
        "body": "The psalm's final verse is its hinge — the *ki* ('for') that provides the warrant for the entire imperative section. The sea is to roar, the rivers to clap, the mountains to sing not because spring has arrived or because harvests have been good, but *because He is coming to judge*. The participial form (*ba* — He is coming) is the same form used in the entrance liturgy of Psalm 24:7-10 ('Lift up your heads... and the King of glory will come in') and in Zechariah 9:9 ('your King is coming to you'). It describes an imminent, certain, already-in-motion arrival.\n\nThe content of the judgment is named twice: *tsedeq* (righteousness) and *meshar* (equity). These are not synonyms chosen for poetic variation alone; they address two different aspects of judicial failure. *Tsedeq* addresses the moral standard: the judgment will accord with God's own righteous character, not with political expedience. *Meshar* (from the root *yashar*, straight, upright) addresses the process: the judgment will be straight — no crooked rulings, no favoritism, no bribery, no procedural distortion. The combination answers the two most common complaints about human justice: that its standards are wrong and that its process is corrupt. YHWH's coming judgment will fail on neither count.\n\nThe canonical trajectory from this verse is wide and specific. Psalm 96:13 uses nearly identical language ('He is coming... to judge the earth; He will judge the world with righteousness and the peoples with His faithfulness'). Isaiah 11:3-5 describes the Branch of Jesse judging the poor with righteousness and the afflicted with equity — using *tsedeq* and *meshar* in the same breath. Acts 17:31 announces that God has fixed a day to judge the world in righteousness through a Man He has appointed, proved by raising Him from the dead. Revelation 19:11 identifies the rider on the white horse as one who 'judges and wages war in righteousness' — *en dikaiosynē*, the Greek equivalent of *tsedeq*. The psalm's final word is eschatology, and the New Testament reads it as Christology: the righteous Judge coming on the clouds is the same One whose right hand and holy arm achieved the victory announced in verse 1.\n\nDouglas Moo and Peter Davids, writing on epistolary texts that draw on the Psalms' eschatological framework, note that the New Testament consistently refuses to detach the comfort of salvation from the urgency of coming judgment. The same character that made YHWH's acts of salvation trustworthy (chesed and emunah, v.3) is the character by which He will judge (tsedeq and meshar, v.9). Believers praise not because judgment is absent but because the Judge is good.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ba* (coming) — participial, ongoing action already in motion. *Shaphat* (judge, twice in v.9) — the full executive authority of a covenant king: to govern, administer, decide, and vindicate the oppressed. *Tsedeq* (righteousness, v.9) — the moral standard; *tsedaqah* (v.2) — the same root, the character already revealed in salvation. *Meshar* (equity) — straightness, from *yashar* (upright); the procedural integrity of the judgment. The psalm opens with *pala* (wonderful things done) and closes with *meshar* (equitable judgment to come) — the two bookends of a God who both rescues and restores."
